solution.p:
The sequence is geometric with a_1 = 5. We find  by dividing \dfrac{10}{3} by 5.
\dfrac{10}{3} \div 5 = \dfrac{2}{3}
Thus, the general term of the series is a_n = 5(\dfrac{2}{3})^{n-1}. We use the formula for a geometric series with n=5,
S_5 = \dfrac{a_6 - a_1}{r-1}
We substitute a_1 = 5,~a_6 = 5(\dfrac{2}{3})^5, and r=\dfrac{2}{3}. Thus
\begin{aligned}[t]
                S_5 \amp = \dfrac{5(\dfrac{2}{3})^5 - 5}{\dfrac{2}{3}-1} = \dfrac{5(\dfrac{32}{243} - 1)}{-\dfrac{1}{3}}\\
                 \amp = 5(\dfrac{32-243}{243})(\dfrac{-3}{1}) \approx 13.02\\ 
                \end{aligned}
